1967112
John_Hay_Whitney
John Hay Whitney (27 August 1904 &ndash; 8 February 1982), colloquially known as Jock Whitney, was Ambassador to the United Kingdom, publisher of the York Herald Tribune, and a member of the family.FamilyBorn on August 27, 1904, in Ellsworth, Maine, Whitney was a descendant of John Whitney, a Puritan who settled in Massachusetts in 1635, as well as of William Bradford, who came over on the Mayflower. His father was Whitney, and his grandfathers were C. Whitney and Hay, both cabinet members. His mother was Hay Whitney.The Payne Whitneys lived around the corner from B. Duke, and his wife and daughter Doris. Whitneys uncle, Hazard Payne, a business partner of D. Rockefeller, arranged the buyout of Dukes competitors to create the Tobacco Co.Jock Whitney attended College. He joined Kappa Epsilon fraternity (Phi chapter), as his father had.  Whitney, his father, grandfather, and great-uncle were oarsmen at Yale, and his father was captain of the crew in 1898. He was a member of and Key. While at Yale, he allegedly coined the term cut for the haircut that now bears the name.After graduating in 1926, Whitney went to University, but the death of his father necessitated his returning home. He inherited a trust fund of $20 million  (approximately $210 million in 2005 dollars), and later inherited four times that amount from his mother.Thoroughbred horse racingWhitney inherited his familys love of horses, a predilection he shared with his sister, Whitney Payson. Jock and his sister ran Stables in the U.S., owned by their mother. In 1928, he became the youngest member ever elected to Jockey Club.Whitney and his first wife Liz raced horses both in the United States and in Europe. He owned Easter Hero who won the 1929 and 1930 editions of the Gold Cup. In the 1929 National, his horse twisted a plate and was beaten by a nose at the finish. Although Whitney entered the Grand National annually, he never again came close to winning.The Whitneys entered four horses in the Derby in the 1930s, Stepenfetchit, which finished 3rd in 1932, Overtime, which finished 5th in 1933, Singing Wood, which finished 8th in 1934, and Heather Broom, which finished 3rd in 1939. Jock Whitney was also an outstanding polo player, with a four-goal handicap, and it was as a sportsman that he made the cover of the March 27, 1933 issue of TIME magazine.Business venturesFreeport Texas Co.In 1929, Whitney was hired as a clerk at the firm of Lee, Higginson, where he met Meade Williams, Jr., the son of the founder of Freeport Texas Co., a sulfur mining company. Williams enlisted his aid in ousting the chairman of his familys company by buying shares of the company. Whitney soon was Freeports biggest shareholder, enabling Williams to sack the chairman and his management team. Williams became Freeports president in 1933 and Whitney was appointed Chairman of the Board.TechnicolorWhitney invested in several Broadway shows, including Arnos 1931 revue Here Goes the Bride, a failure that cost him $100,000, but was more successful as one of the backers  of with Father.An October 1934 Fortune article on the Corporation noted Whitneys interest in pictures. He had met Technicolor head Kalmus at the Race Course. In 1932, Technicolor achieved a breakthrough with its three-strip process. C. Cooper of Radio Pictures approached Whitney with the idea of investing in Technicolor. They joined forces and founded Pictures in 1933, with a distribution deal with RKO to distribute Pioneers films. Whitney and his cousin Vanderbilt Whitney bought a 15% stake in Technicolor.Whitney was also the major investor in O. Selznicks production company, putting up $870,000 and serving as Chairman of the Board. He put up half the money to option Mitchells with the Wind for the Selznick film version, in which he then invested, and later in Rebecca (1940).J.H. Whitney & Co.Whitney & Company is the oldest venture capital firm in the U.S. (Whitneys business partner, C. Schmidt, Sr., in fact, coined the term venture capital.) In 1958, while he was still ambassador to the United Kingdom, his company Whitney Communications Corp. bought the York Herald Tribune, and was its publisher from 1961 to its closure in 1966. Whitney Communications also owned and operated other newspapers, plus magazines and broadcasting stations.Personal lifeJock Whitney purchased the estate in 1930 as a bridal gift for his fiance, the Pennsylvania socialite Mary Elizabeth Liz Altemus. It was a  historic equestrian farm just outside Virginia. The couple divorced in 1940, but Liz Whitney remained there for the rest of her life, becoming an internationally renowned horse breeder and a member of the Thoroughbred Association Hall of Fame.Although married to Altemus, Jock Whitney was romantically linked to Bankhead, Bennett, Goddard and Crawford.  Gable and Lombard met at one of Whitneys parties. In the early 1930s Jock Whitney began an affair with Nina Gore Vidal; at the same time Mary Altemus Whitney had an affair with Nina Vidals husband Eugene Vidal.()  Whitney and Liz divorced in 1940 and in 1942 he married Cushing Roosevelt Whitney, ex-wife of Roosevelt, son of D. Roosevelt, and adopted her two daughters, Kate and Sara Whitney.Whitney met Astaire in York while the former was a student at University and they became lifelong friends, sharing a passion for horse racing. Whitney became a major investor in two of Astaires Broadway stage vehicles, The Band Wagon (1930) and Divorce (1932), and played a crucial role in securing for Astaire a contract with Pictures in 1933, using his contacts with C. Cooper - both men were board members of American Airways whose planes were prominently featured in Astaires breakthrough film with Rogers: Down to Rio (1933).()During the 1970s, Jock Whitney was listed as one of the ten wealthiest men in the world. The residences at his disposal over the years included an estate on Island; a plantation in Georgia; a townhouse and an elegant apartment in Manhattan; a large summer house on Island, near London, Connecticut; a 12-room house in Springs, which the Whitneys used when they attended horse races; a golfing cottage in Georgia, where he was a member of the National Golf Club; and a spacious house in England, near the Racecourse. Mr. Whitney also owned an estate in South Carolina, which he considered his retirement home and where he hoped to spend his final days.Art collectionAmong the paintings in his collection, Jock Whitneys prized possession was the Bal au moulin de la Galette painted in 1876 by the French artist Renoir. In 1990, his widow put the painting up for auction with Sothebys, York and it sold for US$78 million to Japanese businessman, Saito.Military careerWhitney served in the States Army Air Forces as an intelligence officer during War II, assigned to the of Strategic Services. He was taken prisoner by the Germans in southern France, but escaped when the train transporting him to a camp came under Allied fire.Political lifeWhitney was the major backer of D. Eisenhower.  President Eisenhower appointed him States Ambassador to the United Kingdom, a post held sixty years earlier by Whitneys grandfather Hay.  Whitney played a major role in improving Anglo-American relations, which had been severely strained during the 1956 Crisis, when Eisenhower demanded that the British, French and Israelis terminate their invasion of Egypt.PhilanthropyPayne Whitney made substantial gifts to Yale, to the York Presbyterian Hospital, and the York Public Library. After his fathers death, the family built the Whitney Gymnasium at Yale in his honor. The family also financed Whitney Psychiatric Clinic at York Presbyterian Hospital in 1932.Whitney created the John Hay Whitney Foundation for educational projects in 1946. The Foundation provided fellowships to the racially and culturally deprived. He became a major contributor to Yale University, where he served as a Fellow of the Corporation.In 1951, he and his wife Betsey Cushing Whitney donated land from their Greentree estate in New York toward the building of North Shore Hospital. Currently called Shore University Hospital, it is the flagship hospital of the 3rd largest not-for-profit secular healthcare system in the United States, the North Shore-Long Island Jewish Health System.In 1953, Whitney received Hundred Year Association of New Yorks Gold Medal Award in recognition of outstanding contributions to the City of New York.ReferencesExternal links* * Philadelphia Inquirer Obituary 9 Feb 1982*  ja:
1971692
Confederation_of_German_Trade_Unions
The Confederation of German Trade Unions (, DGB) is an organisation (sometimes known as a trade union center) for eight German unions, in total representing more than 7 million people (31 December 2004). It was founded in Munich, 12 October 1949.The DGB coordinates joint demands and activities within the German trade union movement. It represents the member unions in contact with the government authorities, the political parties and the employers organisations. However, the umbrella organisation is not directly involved in bargaining and does not conclude collective labour agreements.Union delegates elect committees for 9 districts, 94 regions and the federal centre. The organisation holds a federal congress every four years. This assembly sets the framework for trade union policies and elects five Federal Executives. Together with the presidents of the member unions they constitute the DGBs executive committee. The members of the executive committee, together with the DGB regional presidents and 70 delegates from the unions, form a Federal Council which meets once a year to make decisions on national issues. The DGB also has a youth organisation, DGB-Jugend.The DGB has its headquarters in Berlin. It is a member of the Trade Union Confederation (ETUC) and the Trade Union Confederation (ITUC). History  Until 1933 As first German confederation of unions at 14 March 1892 the Generalkommission der Gewerkschaften Deutschlands was founded in Halberstadt. It represented 57 national and some local unions with approximate 300,000 people in total. After World War I unions had to reorganise. During a congress in Nuremberg from 30 June until 5 July 1919 the Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund (ADGB) was founded as an umbrella organisation of 52 unions with more than 3 million members. The ADGB may be seen as predecessor of todays DGB. Like today, there also existed a conservative counterpart of lesser importance.Curiously, this conservative organisation was named Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund, DGB. On 2 May 1933 all trade unions were dissolved by the Nazis. 19461949 After World War II German unions had to reorganise once again.On 911 February 1946 the Freier Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund, FDGB was founded in Berlinas a confederation of 15 unions in the occupation zone.On 2325 April 1947 the Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund, DGB was founded in Bielefeldas a confederation of 12 unions in the Germany.Foundations in the American occupation zone:24/25 August 1946: Freier Gewerkschaftsbund Hessen30 August  1 September 1946: Gewerkschaftsbund Wrttemberg-Baden2729 March 1947: Bayerischer GewerkschaftsbundFoundations in the French occupation zone:15/16 February 1947: Gewerkschaftsbund Sd-Wrttemberg und Hohenzollern1/2 March 1947: Badischer Gewerkschaftsbund2 May 1947: Allgemeiner Gewerkschaftsbund Rheinland-PfalzOn 1214 October, the 7 umbrella organisation in Germanymerged into the West German DGB as a confederation of 16 single trade unions.Number of members, 30 June 1949::DGB of the British zone ................................................. 2,885,036:Freier Gewerkschaftsbund Hessen .................................... 397,008:Gewerkschaftsbund Wrttemberg-Baden .......................... 464,905:Bayerischer Gewerkschaftsbund ....................................... 815,161:Gewerkschaftsbund Sd-Wrttemberg und Hohenzollern ... 75,502:Badischer Gewerkschaftsbund ............................................ 92,257:Allgemeiner Gewerkschaftsbund Rheinland-Pfalz ............. 232,117:Total...............................................................................4,961,986 Until today In 1990 the members of the FDGB of the Democratic Republic joined the members of the DGB.Until today many single member unions of the DGB have merged, so recently the DGB only has 8 members.Affiliates Today * IG BAU  Bauen-Agrar-Umwelt (Construction, Agriculture, Environment) 314,568 members  5.08%* IG BCE  Bergbau, Chemie, Energie (Mining, Chemicals, Energy) 675,606 members  10.91%*