Hughes_Mining_Barge
thumb|HMB-1 in San Diego, June 2005.The Hughes Mining Barge, or HMB-1, is a submersible barge about 99 m (324 ft) long, 32 m (106 ft) wide, and more than 27 m (90 ft) tall. The HMB-1 was originally developed as part of Azorian (more widely, but erroneously, known as Project Jennifer), the top-secret effort mounted by the Intelligence Agency to salvage the remains of the Soviet submarine K-129 from the ocean floor. The HMB-1 was designed to be submerged under the Explorer to conceal any salvaged remains from Soviet observers.(After the conclusion of Project Azorian, the HMB-1 was mothballed at the Shipyard in Francisco, California until November, 1982. At that time, the States Navy towed the huge barge to a Martin facility in City, California, where it became a floating drydock for the construction and trials of the Shadow, an experimental ship being tested by the Navy. Sea trials of the Sea Shadow continued until 1986.()()FateThe HMB-1 currently sits along with the Sea Shadow - which is still docked inside the vessel - in the Defense Reserve Fleet at Bay, California.References( * Roy Varner and Wayne Collier A Matter of Risk: The Incredible Inside Story of the CIAs Hughes Glomar Explorer Mission to Raise a Russian Submarine, 1978External links*AZORIAN The Raising of the K-129 / 2009 - 2 Part TV Documentary / Michael White Films Vienna*Photos and details of HMB-1*Overview of Project Jennifer*The Navy Has a Top-Secret Vessel It Wants to Put on Display by Barry Newman - Street Journal - February 24, 2009*Virtual tour inside HMB-1 and Sea Shadow, 2011, includes HMB-1 operating manual.*Google Maps view of The Hughes Mining BargeMining Barge
