John_Aristotle_Phillips
John Aristotle Phillips is a U.S. entrepreneur.A-Bomb KidPhillips was born in August 1955 to Greek immigrant parents and raised in Haven, Connecticut() In 1976, while attending University as a junior undergraduate, he designed a weapon using publicly-available books and papers.() In February 1977, several months after the story first went public, Phillips was contacted by a Pakistani official trying to purchase his bomb design, an incident addressed on the Senate floor by Proxmire and Charles Percy.() Phillips was a celebrity by this time, dubbed the The A-Bomb Kid by the media,() and making a series of television appearances including a featured spot on the game show Tell The Truth.( Phillips was an underachieving student who played the tiger mascot at Princeton games. Hoping to stay at the school, he proposed a paper for a seminar on proliferation outlining the design for an atomic bomb similar to the Nagasaki weapon. According to Phillips supervisor Dyson, a renowned physicist, and professor Feiveson, who held the seminar, Phillips design was not functional,(James Verini: Big Brother Inc.. Vanity Fair online, December 13, 2007) and the story was widely circulated in exaggerated form. Nevertheless, the Bureau of Investigation confiscated Phillipss term paper and a mockup he had constructed in his dormitory room. In 1979 Phillips published his story together with a co-author, David Michaelis, as Mushroom: The True Story of the A-Bomb Kid (ISBN 0-671-82731-6 / ISBN 0-688-03351-2). Political activityPhillips parlayed his celebrity into a brief career as an anti-nuclear activist. In 1980 and 1982 he ran for the States House of Representatives as a Democratic Party candidate in 4th congressional district, losing both times to Republican Stewart McKinney.(Aristotle, Inc.The experience he had gained during his campaigns obtaining the voter list from the state and using it for campaign purposes led him and his brother Dean (who had written a program to handle the list on an II) to found Inc. in 1983,( a non-partisan technology consulting firm for political campaigns which John Philips has since led as the CEO. It specializes in enriching voter lists with personal data from other sources (such as income, ownership or attendance) and data-mining, to assist with micro-targeting of specific voter groups; as of 2007, its database contained detailed information about ca. 175 million U.S. voters and it had about 100 employees.(Aristotle has served every occupant of the House since Reagan, and consults for several top action committees.(Aristotle - Now You Know)In 1998 he spoke of the critical importance to a political campaign of targeting its advertising, including on the wide web.()  In 2009 he observed that 8.9% of registered voters in the United States are ineligible to vote because they have moved away or died.()As of 2007, Phillips lived in San Francisco with his wife and daughter.(See also*States v. The Progressive, et al.*Country ExperimentReferences(External links* John Aristotle Phillips Bio on Aristotle, Incs home page()
