Lanfang_Republic
The Lanfang Republic (modern name in Chinese: , Pinyin: Lnfng Gnghgu) was a Chinese state in Kalimantan in Indonesia that was established by a Hakka Chinese named Lan Pak (Fangbo) () in 1777, until it was ended by Dutch occupation in 1884 (for their part, the Dutch considered their actions in 1884 as breaking up a Chinese uprising). The sultans of Western Borneo imported Chinese laborers in 18th century to work in gold or tin mines. A number of mining communities (kongsi) enjoyed some political autonomy,() but Lanfang is the best known thanks to a history written by Siong-yoen, the son-in-law of the last kapitan of the Lanfang kongsi, which was translated into Dutch in 1885.(.) None of the other Chinese mining settlements in western Kalimantan left written accounts (Heidhues 2001:169).Notes(References. External links*Info at Asiawind.comde LanfangLanfangja:Lanfangha Lan Phngzh:
