Walter_H._Kansteiner,_III
RepublicanWalter H. Kansteiner, III (born November 14, 1955) was the States Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs from June 2001 until November 2003. Career In the late 1980s, Kansteiner was appointed Director of Economic Studies at the on Religion and Democracy.(http://www.fpif.org/commentary/2001/0104kansteiner.html) In May 1989, Kansteiner joined the Departments policy planning staff as Africa director.  He served in this position until June 1991, when he moved to the National Security Council as director for African affairs. In April 1992, he was appointed as the National Security Council Deputy Press Secretary.(http://bushlibrary.tamu.edu/research/papers/1992/92042203.html)As a founding Principal of Scowcroft Group,(http://www.scowcroft.com/html/staff/kansteiner.html) Kansteiner has advised corporations on a wide range of mergers, acquisitions and privatizations throughout Africa in the telecommunications, forestry, mining, financial services, health care and aviation industries.  Kansteiner advised the buy side on the $1.3 billion privatization of Telkom South Africa, to date the largest privatization in Africa. He also was Executive Vice President of W.H. Kansteiner, Inc. in Chicago, an agricultural commodity trading and manufacturing company specializing in tropical commodities in the developing world.(http://www.worldpolicy.org/projects/arms/updates/050701.htm)(http://allafrica.com/stories/200103080004.html)In June 2001 he was appointed by Powell as Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs.  In 2003, he left the post, citing family reasons.(http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ho/po/12045.htm)(http://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/03/20020318.html) He was appointed in April 2004 as independent non-executive director to the board of Limited.(http://www.spescom.co.za/news.asp?menuID144)Kansteiner is on the Board of Directors of the Council on Africa,(http://www.africacncl.org/About_CCA/board.asp) Development Foundation,(http://www.leadershipdirectories.com/fmfyb9.htm) and Rutile.(http://www.kfmb.com/story.php?id16349)FamilyKansteiner is married, has two children Beverly and Chalker, and resides in Middleburg, Virginia. His wife, Frances Kansteiner,  is from Alabama.  Her father Houston Blount, ran Vulcan Materials for many years and his brother Winton M. Red Blount, Postmaster General in Nixons cabinet. She is a Board member of the Foundation. Red and his brother, Houston, founded Blount Brothers Construction, a large construction and manufacturing firm formerly headquartered in Montgomery.  It was later renamed Blount International and moved to Portland, Oregon. Frances Kansteiner was an Officer, Director and Advisor to the Foundation. http://www.wild.org/about/board.html  She also on the board of Stratford Hall.Memberships and Affiliations*States Department of Defense, Strategic Minerals Task Force*Senior Associate of Forum for International Policy*Member of on Foreign Relations*Senior Associate of the for Strategic and International Studies*Steering Committee and International Advisory Board Member of New Global Economy Project*Board member of WildlifeDirectExternal links* US Department of State: Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Walter H. Kansteiner to Travel to Angola and Nigeria* Excerpts at Special Briefing - leaves U.S. State Dept by Walter H. Kansteiner III, Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs, States Department of State October 28, 2003, Washington, D.C.* http://www.rasmusen.org/x/archives/c/archives/cat_cia.html* Letter to Bush Regarding Kansteiner Cynthia McKinney, Member of Congress* Bio - Walter KansteinerReferences
